Russia Stocks Sink to 6-Month Low on Oil, Europe Debt Concern

-- B y   J a s o n   C o r c o r a n
-- 
2011-05-23T15:53:35Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-23/russia-stocks-sink-to-6-month-low-on-oil-europe-debt-concern.html
Russian stocks dropped to their
lowest in almost six months as oil fell and concern  Europe ’s
debt crisis will hurt the economic recovery curbed investor
appetite for riskier assets.  The Micex Index of 30 stocks slipped 1.9 percent to
1,573.14by the 6:45 p.m. close in Moscow, its lowest close since
Nov 30. OAO Gazprom Neft, an oil producer, lost 3 percent. OAO
Gazprom, Russia’s gas export monopoly, fell 3.5 percent, as
Credit Suisse AG downgraded its shares to “underperform” from
“neutral.” OAO Sberbank, the country’s largest bank, decreased
2.6 percent. The dollar-denominated RTS Index slumped 3.3
percent to 1,765.65, its biggest loss in over a month.  Crude for July delivery sank as much as 3.1 percent to
$96.37 a barrel in New York onEurope’s sovereign debt crisis
will spread.  Fitch Ratings  cut  Greece  by three grades and
 Standard & Poor’s  said Italy was at risk of a downgrade. Spanish
Prime Minister Jose Luis Rodriguez Zapatero’s Socialist party
suffered its worst defeat in more than 30 years in local
elections amid a backlash over austerity measures.  “The more speculative investment in Russia is leaving
town,” Marco Casas, Moscow-based vice-president for equity
sales at Otkritie Financial Corp., said in e-mailed comments
today.  Fund Flows  Russia-focused equity funds had their biggest weekly
outflows in five years in the week to May 18, according to
UralSib Financial Corp., which cited data from EPFR Global in a
report on May 20. VTB Capital said $311 million of the $353
million outflow was from exchange traded funds, and represented
speculative investments or “hot money,” according to a May 20
note.  Copper for three-month delivery slid as much as 3.7 percent
on the London Metal Exchange. Tin, nickel and lead also
declined. OAO GMK Norilsk Nickel,  Russia ’s biggest mining
company, slipped 1.8 percent.  To contact the reporter on this story:
